WEBVTT

00:00.739 --> 00:02.201
- What's she doing here?
- You hired her.

00:02.466 --> 00:03.883
- I did?
- I'm confused.

00:04.099 --> 00:04.802
Hello, David.

00:06.150 --> 00:08.567
Why can't two grown
drunk people act

00:08.830 --> 00:10.787
like two grown drunk people?

00:11.875 --> 00:14.561
That's when my dad
came up with the idea to make a clone.

00:14.871 --> 00:17.445
He used you to save your brother.

00:18.217 --> 00:20.219
He was diagnosed with
leukaemia a year ago.

00:20.471 --> 00:22.089
Do you got any proof that the
therapy caused the stroke?

00:22.395 --> 00:24.937
I think that the Peterson boy's
immune system over-responded.

00:25.260 --> 00:27.191
- But you don't know.
- Neither does Booker.

00:27.717 --> 00:29.075
The boy was sick.

00:29.579 --> 00:31.752
He died of a disease that
we were trying to save him from.

00:32.046 --> 00:34.680
You studied the therapy.
Does it work or doesn't it work?

00:35.115 --> 00:37.035
He might have suffered a stroke
with or without the treatment.

00:37.333 --> 00:38.655
You're willing to bet
lives on that, Carlos?

00:38.971 --> 00:41.319
The question that we are
dealing with here is:

00:41.553 --> 00:44.793
if 3,000 kids get this treatment,
will 1 die or 1,000?

00:45.353 --> 00:47.040
He's in a coma, David.

00:47.408 --> 00:49.181
- Who?
- Justin... Ricci!

00:49.689 --> 00:50.629
You....!

00:51.224 --> 00:54.112
You signed that
boy's death sentence!

00:54.489 --> 00:55.227
You!

00:57.035 --> 00:59.603
If Mick... you know,
he had a dream too,

00:59.819 --> 01:02.234
- he should like totally go for it.
- Absolutely.

01:02.505 --> 01:04.137
- And I should help him.
- Of course.

01:04.441 --> 01:05.666
- Yeah, okay, bye.
- Bye.

01:09.994 --> 01:12.779
This here is your
Mr. George Edward Plane.

01:13.620 --> 01:15.441
Oh, you're fucking beautiful.

01:15.967 --> 01:19.045
I found it.
A sample of the 1918 flu.

01:19.559 --> 01:20.730
A perfect specimen.

01:22.000 --> 01:28.074
Advertise your product or brand here
contact www.OpenSubtitles.org today

02:48.883 --> 02:51.932
1x07 - Faint Hope

02:56.737 --> 02:57.969
A hundred and two,

02:58.253 --> 02:59.925
a hundred and two.
It's Kobe in the heat.

03:02.685 --> 03:04.396
You ever consider table tennis?

03:05.262 --> 03:07.132
I thought you were on a flight to Houston.

03:08.262 --> 03:10.114
The cab's on its way.

03:10.448 --> 03:12.431
How's the pathology
on Justin Ricci going?

03:12.621 --> 03:14.288
I should have results soon.

03:16.641 --> 03:18.600
- You're throwing it at me?
- To you.

03:18.703 --> 03:21.734
David, we ran all the tests on
the gene treatment. It checked out.

03:22.269 --> 03:23.521
Shut up and play.

03:24.217 --> 03:25.941
The kid's in a coma, Carlos.

03:26.315 --> 03:29.922
Four hours after taking the treatment
in the trial that I sent him to.

03:35.538 --> 03:37.302
I should have been more closely involved.

03:38.327 --> 03:41.036
Oh, what? You're saying you're
the only one who could have done it right?

03:45.472 --> 03:47.534
The whole lab worked on it, David.

03:48.344 --> 03:50.098
If something was missed,

03:52.911 --> 03:54.034
then we all missed it.

03:54.445 --> 03:57.305
Well, I don't know about you,
but I'm not used to missing.

04:10.911 --> 04:12.108
Have a nice flight.

04:32.568 --> 04:33.739
Hey, David.

04:34.896 --> 04:36.315
Hit me.

04:37.372 --> 04:40.505
Oh, I got the brain scans
you ordered on the kids that survived.

04:40.878 --> 04:41.793
Let me see.

04:42.512 --> 04:44.755
Okay. Of course, these kids didn't have
a blast crisis

04:44.854 --> 04:47.384
or a cytokine storm.
They look pretty normal.

04:52.172 --> 04:54.664
- What do you think?
- I think they look pretty normal.

04:55.103 --> 04:55.824
Mayko?

04:56.868 --> 04:58.316
Isn't it a little early for that?

04:58.693 --> 05:00.089
It's never too early for basketball.

05:00.558 --> 05:03.004
Did you rerun the comparisons
on Peterson's and Ricci's genes?

05:03.463 --> 05:05.409
- You want to see the cyto genetic workup?
- Yeah.

05:08.856 --> 05:11.735
And all the kids in the trials
had the same chromosomal abnormality?

05:11.936 --> 05:13.579
Uh-hmm. An 8-11 translocation.

05:14.308 --> 05:17.573
It's just the kind of messed up chromosomal
you expect in an AML patient.

05:17.967 --> 05:20.462
Are we sure the RNA inhibitor
got to the leukaemia cells?

05:20.778 --> 05:23.967
In all the cases. The viral injection did
what it was supposed to do.

05:23.968 --> 05:24.968
Oh, fuck.

05:25.883 --> 05:27.806
Look, David. I know I was pushing you.

05:28.093 --> 05:30.143
- I mean, if you had more time you...
- And I would have made the same call

05:30.446 --> 05:32.886
and I would still be wondering
why Peterson and Ricci

05:33.077 --> 05:34.813
reacted differently to the treats.

05:45.349 --> 05:47.982
There's nothing wrong with
the decision to continue the trial.

05:48.000 --> 05:50.067
We made the right call at the time.

05:50.115 --> 05:51.939
Can you explain what
happened to the Ricci boy?

05:52.267 --> 05:55.412
He had a stroke like the Peterson kid,
but not because of the same thing.

05:55.601 --> 05:56.647
What then?

05:57.169 --> 06:00.334
Peterson had what we
call a cytokine storm,

06:00.747 --> 06:04.095
which is too many immune activating
proteins in his system.

06:04.996 --> 06:06.084
And that's bad?

06:06.185 --> 06:08.352
Too many of anything in the body is bad.

06:09.299 --> 06:14.021
- Okay, what about Justin Ricci?
- Ah, he had what we call blast crisis.

06:14.404 --> 06:16.901
Blast cells are these little baby cells,
cancerous ones,

06:17.262 --> 06:20.983
and you get too many of those guys in
your system and the same thing can result.

06:21.021 --> 06:21.868
You know: coma, death.

06:21.869 --> 06:24.207
But caused by
something totally different.

06:24.561 --> 06:26.877
Exactly. So, is it the treatment,

06:26.878 --> 06:28.157
or is it a coincidence,

06:28.594 --> 06:30.674
something to do with the two kids,

06:30.775 --> 06:33.352
or is it just plain old bad luck?

06:34.677 --> 06:36.950
- Well?
- Place your bets.

07:39.498 --> 07:41.114
Excuse me, can I help you?

07:41.509 --> 07:44.178
Yeah, I need everything you've got
on Justin Ricci for the last 24 hours:

07:44.523 --> 07:47.228
Blood tests, brain scans,
a copy of this chart, everything.

07:47.861 --> 07:48.522
Okay.

08:22.917 --> 08:23.822
Carlito!

08:32.155 --> 08:34.346
I was just thinking of you.

08:35.375 --> 08:36.964
You look good.

08:37.095 --> 08:38.369
I look good?

08:39.789 --> 08:42.841
Oh, my God! Carlos! You're going blind!

08:46.909 --> 08:51.380
I didn't know what to get you,
so I emptied out the airport gift shop.

08:52.307 --> 08:54.891
Blue Jays mug, salt water taffy,

08:55.714 --> 08:57.707
maple leaf-shaped, maple fudge.

08:58.540 --> 09:01.460
Carlos, how am I supposed
to keep my girlish figure?

09:06.913 --> 09:09.078
Why didn't you
let me know sooner?

09:09.448 --> 09:11.631
I did. You're here.

09:27.732 --> 09:30.180
My T-cell count's not so hot, huh?

09:31.220 --> 09:33.526
Your CD4+ is 11%.

09:34.834 --> 09:37.238
There are things we can do.

09:37.610 --> 09:39.419
Are we talking cure?

09:40.727 --> 09:42.879
We're talking quality of life, Lloyd.

09:43.278 --> 09:46.796
Ah, give me a break.
What about something experimental?

09:47.178 --> 09:50.515
Some of this cutting edge technology
my broker's always telling me about.

09:51.184 --> 09:55.442
- There's nothing on the market.
- Then we go off-market.

09:56.054 --> 09:59.359
Carlos, what do you know about
long-term non-progressors?

10:00.437 --> 10:02.084
I've dated a few.

10:05.174 --> 10:07.724
You haven't lost your sense of humour.

10:10.810 --> 10:11.582
David.

10:11.905 --> 10:12.579
Uh-huh?

10:12.750 --> 10:14.065
Can I grab a signature from you?

10:14.231 --> 10:15.006
What for?

10:15.425 --> 10:17.572
I put together the patent application.

10:18.196 --> 10:19.394
Oh, yeah.

10:22.061 --> 10:25.327
Flu strain 777456.

10:26.901 --> 10:28.049
It sounds kind of dull.

10:28.939 --> 10:31.056
Government protocol.
It's all very official.

10:31.527 --> 10:33.973
Hmm. She'll always
be my Spanish lady.

10:34.693 --> 10:37.574
So, after I file, do you want me
to get it over to the WHO?

10:37.888 --> 10:40.247
- What for?
- A vaccine.

10:40.774 --> 10:42.486
Who decided that?

10:43.148 --> 10:45.601
They're the biggest, fastest lab equipped
to make the vaccine.

10:45.943 --> 10:49.567
- I thought it was a no-brainer.
- No. None. No data. Nothing leaves here.

10:49.977 --> 10:52.687
David, we have a pending patent.
We're protected, they can't...

10:53.015 --> 10:54.902
like they even would, but they can't rip us off.

10:55.437 --> 10:59.259
I just don't want the WHO, or any lab
for that matter, working on my shit.

10:59.414 --> 11:02.019
- Our shit.
- Yeah. You know what I mean.

11:02.455 --> 11:04.905
No, actually, I don't know what you mean.

11:05.702 --> 11:07.871
We're going to make a vaccine right here.

11:08.448 --> 11:10.677
And then we'll think
about letting it out.

11:10.937 --> 11:12.548
You're not serious!

11:12.955 --> 11:15.547
Do I look like
I'm wearing a clown costume?

11:15.933 --> 11:18.756
David, the World Health Organization
has more manpower, more equipment,

11:19.102 --> 11:21.551
they could probably come up with a
vaccine in less than a year.

11:21.803 --> 11:25.400
What's the hurry? We found her,
I want to go all the way with her.

11:26.832 --> 11:28.750
Okay, so this is like an ego thing?

11:29.287 --> 11:30.491
Yeah, okay, I'll go with that.

11:31.078 --> 11:34.805
Jill, file the patent and we're going
to make the vaccine right here, okay?

11:36.138 --> 11:37.906
- Whatever you say, boss.
- Thank you.

11:45.279 --> 11:47.081
HIV is killing my CD4s

11:47.144 --> 11:49.945
and my CD8s aren't going
to respond to a head cold,

11:50.288 --> 11:51.824
let alone something more serious.

11:52.440 --> 11:55.231
They're making progress with the
virus every day, Lloyd.

11:55.739 --> 11:56.776
No, I've read everything:

11:57.189 --> 12:00.827
From the effects of potent anti-retroviral
therapy on Kaposi's Sarcoma,

12:01.349 --> 12:05.414
to the uses of labelled glucose
to study lymphocyte replication.

12:05.981 --> 12:08.248
And finally, you got to
long term non-progressors?

12:08.690 --> 12:13.061
These people, Carlos, they're HIV-positive
and they never get AIDS.

12:13.997 --> 12:15.555
They can save me.

12:16.512 --> 12:18.459
You can save me.

12:24.476 --> 12:27.123
Welcome. Between Quebec City
and the Atlantic Ocean

12:27.424 --> 12:29.544
lies a region of stunning beauty,

12:29.832 --> 12:31.601
a majestic landscapes of dense forests

12:31.922 --> 12:34.874
and breath-taking fjords carved out
by ancient glaciers.

12:38.242 --> 12:39.463
Are you okay?

12:39.962 --> 12:42.672
Oh yeah, I'm just a little bit stiff
from sitting down so...

12:43.049 --> 12:45.261
Mick, your nose is like, bleeding.

12:45.544 --> 12:47.979
Shit! No, it's okay,
it happens all the time.

12:50.030 --> 12:52.315
Yeah, yeah, it happens
to my mom too,

12:52.547 --> 12:54.897
and, she blames it on thin blood,

12:55.377 --> 12:58.943
but I think it's because
she's a record producer. Never mind.

12:59.839 --> 13:03.251
Don't worry, just keep reading,
it'll stop in a couple minutes.

13:05.581 --> 13:08.499
Here the Saguenay River meets
the mighty St. Lawrence

13:08.905 --> 13:11.790
and many species of whales:
the finback, humpback,

13:12.397 --> 13:15.329
hunchback, horseback and paperback...

13:15.648 --> 13:17.474
What are talking about?

13:18.373 --> 13:19.990
Just seeing if you're listening.

13:41.141 --> 13:42.891
- Do you have a minute?
- What do you want, Wes?

13:43.688 --> 13:46.359
Caroline asked me to go
through Booker's finances.

13:46.814 --> 13:47.747
Why?

13:48.307 --> 13:51.411
We became aware that he gets stock options
if the treatment goes to market.

13:52.155 --> 13:56.036
You know, there's this little thing
in the Western world called capitalism, Wes.

13:56.187 --> 13:58.430
It can get ugly,
but we allow individuals to compete

13:58.511 --> 13:59.908
for their own financial gain.

14:00.174 --> 14:03.373
Well, he stands to gain a lot of
money if this gene therapy is approved.

14:03.710 --> 14:05.487
Don't you find that a bit unethical?

14:05.802 --> 14:08.321
He has a PhD in molecular biology

14:08.613 --> 14:10.697
and he gets paid less than
an interior decorator.

14:10.873 --> 14:12.238
That's what's unethical.

14:12.387 --> 14:15.493
I'm just suggesting that Booker has a little
incentive to push this therapy through.

14:16.284 --> 14:18.079
Okay, so the
thinking is what?

14:18.462 --> 14:19.900
That after 20 years in a lab,

14:20.274 --> 14:23.077
Booker's going to throw away his reputation
for a couple of stock options?

14:24.157 --> 14:28.215
Actually, $2,750,000 worth
of stock options.

14:31.356 --> 14:32.916
Oh.

14:37.209 --> 14:38.150
Yeah?

14:38.709 --> 14:41.336
- Hey, Carlos, where are you?
- I'm still in Houston.

14:41.715 --> 14:43.406
- How's...
- Not good.

14:43.934 --> 14:47.160
David, do you know about the research
Judy Beewick has been doing on HIV?

14:47.582 --> 14:50.073
- Yeah, it's pretty hot there.
- Do you know her?

14:51.867 --> 14:54.059
Carlos, I hope you're not
thinking what I think you're...

14:54.162 --> 14:55.522
Do you know her, David?

14:57.074 --> 14:59.009
We've met at conferences.

14:59.044 --> 15:01.198
- Have you pissed her off?
- Probably,

15:01.468 --> 15:03.634
eventually, I piss everybody off.

15:03.979 --> 15:08.012
She works with HIV-positive people
who never get AIDS,

15:08.013 --> 15:09.164
non-progressors.

15:09.489 --> 15:11.120
Wait a minute, how bad is your friend?

15:11.745 --> 15:13.924
His HIV RNA is at a million copies.

15:15.168 --> 15:16.289
Jesus, Carlos, I'm sorry.

15:17.679 --> 15:20.920
- Hello, David?
- Carlos? Carlos, you are still there?

15:21.578 --> 15:23.137
- Hello?
- Call me back.

15:24.777 --> 15:26.726
Great! Ow!

15:27.193 --> 15:27.673
Shit!

15:28.906 --> 15:30.612
What the hell happened?

15:31.223 --> 15:33.203
- Darkness!
- My LC/MS run.

15:33.500 --> 15:35.341
I'll lose the vacuum,
I need emergency back up.

15:36.025 --> 15:39.370
Bob, relax, it's already tied
into the emergency generator.

15:45.769 --> 15:48.632
- Right. It looks like it's citywide.
- Are we secure?

15:49.001 --> 15:50.937
We're good, the system's on back-up.

15:50.938 --> 15:52.728
They say it could be as bad as '03.

15:53.151 --> 15:56.668
Not just Toronto, oh,
but the entire North-Eastern seaboard.

15:57.013 --> 15:58.602
I have an announcement to make.

15:59.051 --> 16:01.420
I will be having scrambled
leftovers at my place tonight

16:01.933 --> 16:04.097
for anyone stranded
without a gas stove.

16:05.487 --> 16:07.144
- Bingo!
- Free food!

16:13.254 --> 16:15.555
Our cells have padlocks,

16:15.556 --> 16:18.332
which HIV needs a key to open.

16:18.682 --> 16:21.330
Long-term non-progressors' cells have

16:21.331 --> 16:23.448
padlocks without keyholes.

16:24.441 --> 16:25.872
HIV can't get in.

16:26.159 --> 16:29.935
- So, how do you change your lock?
- Stem cells.

16:32.857 --> 16:34.010
It's me.

16:34.752 --> 16:36.294
In the dark, how about you?

16:36.429 --> 16:39.422
We should boil the drinking
water 3 to 5 minutes, not 35 minutes.

16:40.110 --> 16:42.082
No power in Baltimore?
How big is this?

16:44.717 --> 16:46.065
Any chance it's terrorism?

16:47.592 --> 16:51.037
Congresswoman Schuller, I don't think
being trapped in an elevator's funny.

16:51.753 --> 16:54.003
No. Right, right, save your batteries.

16:54.004 --> 16:54.959
Okay, good night.

16:55.745 --> 16:57.582
I'm eating at David's tonight.

16:58.666 --> 17:01.646
Wow! Hey Mom, you have
to go out and look at the stars.

17:02.132 --> 17:04.640
No, Mom, electricity doesn't
hold up a balcony!

17:05.781 --> 17:06.984
Look at the stars.

17:07.731 --> 17:09.494
The stars are unbelievable.

17:10.210 --> 17:12.582
Just like when I was back
in Vietnam.

17:13.733 --> 17:16.731
Diane! No, I'm sorry sweetie,
I'm losing you.

17:18.796 --> 17:22.450
Can you e-mail me?
No, that's not going to work.

17:23.098 --> 17:24.768
Hello? Diane?

17:27.288 --> 17:29.336
- So, are you coming for dinner?
- Hi!

17:30.824 --> 17:33.367
Uh, no, thank you.

17:33.546 --> 17:35.382
You're mad about the patent.

17:37.126 --> 17:40.138
No, David, you're the boss. All right?

17:40.339 --> 17:42.995
Well, is this about Chicago?

17:44.633 --> 17:46.052
What? No!

17:46.820 --> 17:48.773
Why aren't you coming for dinner?

17:50.129 --> 17:52.423
Because! I don't know--

17:52.895 --> 17:55.149
It's dark and I'm going to go home.

17:55.350 --> 17:58.226
Have a bubble bath, climb into bed.

17:59.312 --> 18:00.758
Can I come?

18:00.959 --> 18:03.169
You're hosting a dinner party.

18:05.074 --> 18:07.350
Well, not all night!

18:22.896 --> 18:24.480
Come on in, it's open.

18:29.171 --> 18:31.027
Oh hey, Bob.
Come on in, what's up?

18:31.890 --> 18:36.079
I brought wine, I had some left over.
My cousin brought it.

18:36.637 --> 18:37.870
Great, come on in.

18:38.109 --> 18:40.174
Gamelon doesn't like
being alone in the dark.

18:40.405 --> 18:41.661
- Well, where is she?
- Outside.

18:42.041 --> 18:43.841
You want her to come in?

18:49.458 --> 18:50.534
Behave yourself.

18:50.835 --> 18:51.928
Go! Go!

18:53.528 --> 18:56.890
Hey, hi! So what are
we having for dinner?

18:58.266 --> 19:00.461
I brought wine, I didn't
want it to go bad.

19:00.896 --> 19:01.864
Ah hello, Mayko.

19:02.143 --> 19:04.727
Yeah, okay, so I froze it
in my ice cube trays.

19:05.262 --> 19:07.610
- That's a good idea.
- Now, it's melting.

19:07.801 --> 19:09.308
Think of it as ice wine.

19:15.736 --> 19:17.906
- Morrison.
- Caroline, it's me Digby.

19:18.109 --> 19:20.972
- You guys still in the dark over there?
- Yeah. We are.

19:21.179 --> 19:23.869
Our cell phones are off and on
so you better get to your point.

19:24.019 --> 19:27.197
Right, I've got an update on our friend
Martin Jamieson aka William Zanzinger.

19:27.498 --> 19:27.989
Shoot.

19:28.272 --> 19:30.083
It turns out we're not the only ones
looking for him.

19:30.370 --> 19:31.645
- Who else?
- Oh, you name it!

19:31.941 --> 19:35.327
The South-Africans, Pakistanis, I believe
the American expression is "can of worms".

19:35.687 --> 19:38.564
- Yeah. Why Pakistan?
- I don't know yet.

19:39.356 --> 19:41.979
But wasn't that scientist
that was murdered outside your office...

19:42.157 --> 19:44.721
Hira Khan, yeah. She was Pakistani.

19:45.070 --> 19:47.149
The closer we get, the bigger it gets.

19:47.595 --> 19:49.166
- Caroline?
- Digby?

19:49.967 --> 19:51.809
- Hello? Hello?
- Hello?

19:55.033 --> 19:55.780
Thanks.

20:00.177 --> 20:01.965
What do you say?
Zucchini or courgettes?

20:02.713 --> 20:03.771
It's eggplant, Bob.

20:04.285 --> 20:06.882
I know the difference
between an aubergine and courgette.

20:07.232 --> 20:09.118
I don't understand
the question then, what do you...

20:09.428 --> 20:12.759
So, this is kind of romantic.
Candlelight, a dog...

20:12.901 --> 20:15.571
Did you have a nice day at
the office today, honey?

20:15.625 --> 20:18.411
Why, yes dear, very nice,
I schtuped my secretary at lunch.

20:18.694 --> 20:20.859
Oh again? You are a devil, aren't you?

20:21.063 --> 20:23.023
Uh-huh, and then, I made
enough crack cocaine to buy you

20:23.139 --> 20:24.910
that little house in the Annex
you've had your eye on.

20:25.108 --> 20:27.717
Oh, you are so sweet. Then,
I'm going to stop seeing the pool boy.

20:31.807 --> 20:34.007
Any new thoughts on the
gene treatment?

20:34.267 --> 20:37.375
I'm thinking maybe they should revisit
the whole immune response in animals.

20:37.963 --> 20:39.561
You mean, stop the trials?

20:45.766 --> 20:49.459
I'm sorry. Gamelon's been having
